    <h2>Group A: Attemps any TWO questions (2 x 10 = 20)</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>How do you plot the function on graph? Determine whether the function f(x) = x<sup>2</sup> is injective, surjective or bijective with reasons. Solve the recurrence relation a<sub>n</sub> = 6a<sub>n-1</sub> – 9a<sub>n-2</sub> with initial conditions a<sub>0</sub> = 1 and a<sub>1</sub> = 6.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><div class="flex-1 overflow-hidden">
<div class="react-scroll-to-bottom--css-mxclb-79elbk h-full dark:bg-gray-800">
<div class="react-scroll-to-bottom--css-mxclb-1n7m0yu">
<div class="flex flex-col items-center text-sm dark:bg-gray-800">
<div class="group w-full text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 border-b border-black/10 dark:border-gray-900/50 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-[#444654]">
<div class="text-base gap-4 md:gap-6 md:max-w-2xl lg:max-w-2xl xl:max-w-3xl p-4 md:py-6 flex lg:px-0 m-auto">
<div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]">
<div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3">
<div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap">
<div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light">To plot a function on a graph, we will follow following steps:</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="w-full h-32 md:h-48 flex-shrink-0">
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>Determine the domain and range of the function. The domain is the set of all possible input values (x-values) for the function, and the range is the set of all possible output values (y-values) for the function.</li>
<li>Choose a suitable scale for the x and y axes based on the domain and range of the function.</li>
<li>Plot a few key points on the graph by selecting values of x and evaluating the function to get the corresponding y-value. These points should be representative of the function&#8217;s behavior.</li>
<li>Connect the points with a smooth curve that accurately represents the function&#8217;s behavior. If the function has sharp corners or vertical asymptotes, indicate them on the graph.</li>
<li>Label the axes and give the graph a title that indicates the function being plotted.</li>
<li>Check the graph to make sure it accurately represents the function and that all important features are clearly visible.</li>
</ol>
<p>Now, let&#8217;s examine f(x) = x^2, where function is injective, surjective or bijective:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>f(x) is not injective because, for example, f(-2) = f(2) = 4. So, distinct elements of the domain (-2 and 2) are mapped to the same element in the range (4).</li>
<li>f(x) is not surjective because, for example, there is no real number x such that f(x) = -1. This is because the square of any real number is non-negative.</li>
<li>Since f(x) is neither injective nor surjective, it is not bijective.</li>
</ul>
<p>Therefore, the function f(x) = x^2 is neither injective, surjective, nor bijective over the set of real numbers.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" decoding="async" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/users/684/1677325413-CamScanner%2002-25-2023%2017.27_1.jpg?ssl=1" alt=""> <img data-recalc-dims="1" decoding="async" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/users/684/1677325388-CamScanner%2002-25-2023%2017.27_2.jpg?ssl=1" alt=""></p>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>A group of 8 scientist is composed of 5 chemist and 3 biologist. In how many ways can a committe of 5 be formed that has 3 chemist and 2 biologist? Using mathematical induction prove that 1<sup>3</sup> + 2<sup>3</sup> + 3<sup>3</sup> + ……………….. + n<sup>3</sup> = n<sup>2</sup>(n + 1)<sup>2</sup> / 4) for n ≥ 1.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>To find the number of ways to form a committee of 5 scientists with 3 chemists and 2 biologists, we can use the combination formula:</p>
<p>C(5,3) * C(3,2)</p>
<p>where C(n,r) represents the number of combinations of r objects that can be chosen from a set of n objects.</p>
<p>C(5,3) represents the number of ways to choose 3 chemists from a group of 5 chemists, and C(3,2) represents the number of ways to choose 2 biologists from a group of 3 biologists.</p>
<p>Evaluating these expressions, we get:</p>
<p>C(5,3) * C(3,2) = (5!)/(3!<em>(5-3)!) * (3!)/(2!</em>(3-2)!)</p>
<p>= (10) * (3)</p>
<p>= 30</p>
<p>Therefore, there are 30 ways to form a committee of 5 scientists with 3 chemists and 2 biologists from a group of 5 chemists and 3 biologists.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Numberical Part:</strong></span></p>
<p>Solution:</p>
<p>Let P(n): 1<sup>3</sup> + 2<sup>3</sup> + 3<sup>3</sup> + &#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;.. + n<sup>3</sup> = n<sup>2</sup>(n + 1)<sup>2</sup> / 4)</p>
<p><strong>For n = 1,</strong></p>
<p>LHS = 1<sup>3</sup> = 1</p>
<p>RHS = 1<sup>2</sup> ( 1 + 1)<sup>2</sup> / 4 = 1</p>
<p>Hence, LHS = RHS</p>
<p>Therefore, P(n) is true for n = 1</p>
<p><strong>Assume that P(k) is true</strong></p>
<p>1<sup>3</sup> + 2<sup>3</sup> + 3<sup>3</sup> + &#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;.. + k<sup>3</sup> = k<sup>2</sup>(k + 1)<sup>2</sup> / 4)   &#8212;&#8212;- (i)</p>
<p>We will prove that P(k+1) is true</p>
<p>1<sup>3</sup> + 2<sup>3</sup> + 3<sup>3</sup> + &#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;.. + k<sup>3</sup> + (k+1)<sup>3</sup> = \(\left ( \frac{(k+1)^2((k+1) + 1)^2}{4} \right )\)</p>
<p>1<sup>3</sup> + 2<sup>3</sup> + 3<sup>3</sup> + &#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;.. + k<sup>3</sup> + (k+1)<sup>3</sup> = \(\left ( \frac{(k+1)^2(k+2)^2}{4} \right )\)      &#8212;&#8212;&#8211; (2)</p>
<p>We have to prove P(k+1) from P(k) i.e. (2) from (1)</p>
<p>From Equation (1):</p>
<p>1<sup>3</sup> + 2<sup>3</sup> + 3<sup>3</sup> + &#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;.. + k<sup>3</sup> = k<sup>2</sup>(k + 1)<sup>2</sup> / 4)</p>
<p>After adding (k+1)<sup>3</sup> both sides,</p>
<p>1<sup>3</sup> + 2<sup>3</sup> + 3<sup>3</sup> + &#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;.. + k<sup>3</sup> + (k+1)<sup>3</sup> = \(\frac{k^2(k+1)^2}{4}\) + (k + 1)<sup>3</sup></p>
<p>= \(\frac{k^2(k+1)^2 + 4(k + 1)^3}{4}\)</p>
<p>= \(\frac{(k+1)^2(k^2 + 4k + 4)}{4}\)</p>
<p>= \(\frac{(k+1)^2(k^2 + 2k + 2k + 4)}{4}\)</p>
<p>= \(\frac{(k+1)^2((k+1)(k+2))}{4}\)</p>
<p>= \(\frac{(k+1)^2 (k+2)^2}{4}\)</p>
<p>Thus, 1<sup>3</sup> + 2<sup>3</sup> + 3<sup>3</sup> + &#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;&#8230;.. + k<sup>3</sup> + (k+1)<sup>3</sup> = \(\left ( \frac{(k+1)^2(k+2)^2}{4} \right )\)</p>
<p>i.e. P(k+1) is true whenever P(k) is true</p>
<p>Therefore, By the principle of mathematical induction, P(n) is true for n, where n is natural number.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
