<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>Show that the relation R = {(a, b): |a – b| is even} is an equivalence relation in the set of integers. Given the following transport network with the edges labeled with their capacities, find all S-D and their capacities and What is the minimum capacity?</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-6461 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/ds-qnbank-2078-sd-ct.jpg?resize=369%2C215&ssl=1" alt="" width="369" height="215" srcset="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/ds-qnbank-2078-sd-ct.jpg?w=860&ssl=1 860w, https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/ds-qnbank-2078-sd-ct.jpg?resize=768%2C447&ssl=1 768w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 369px) 100vw, 369px" /></p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A relation R on a set A is an equivalence relation it is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive.</p>
<p>Let A = {1, 2, 3, 4} be a set of integers.</p>
<p>A x A = {1, 2, 3, 4} x {1, 2, 3, 4}</p>
<p>= {(1, 1) (1, 2) (1, 3) (1, 4) (2, 1) (2, 2) (2, 3) (2, 4) (3, 1) (3, 2) (3, 3) (3, 4) (4, 1) (4, 2) (4, 3) (4, 4)}</p>
<p>We have conditions,</p>
<p>R = {(a, b) : |a -b| is even|</p>
<p>So,</p>
<p>R = {(1, 1) (1, 3) (2, 2) (2, 4) (3, 1) (3, 3) (4, 2) (4, 4)}</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>For reflexive,</strong></span></p>
<p>∀ a ∈ A, (a, a) ∈ R</p>
<p>(1, 1) ∈ R</p>
<p>(1, 3) ∉ R</p>
<p>(2, 2) ∈ R</p>
<p>(2, 4) ∉ R</p>
<p>(3, 1) ∉ R</p>
<p>(3, 3) ∈ R</p>
<p>(4, 2) ∉ R</p>
<p>(4, 4) ∈ R</p>
<p>The relation is reflexive</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>For symmetric:</strong></span></p>
<p>if  (a, b) ∈ A then (b, a) ∈ R</p>
<p>(1, 1) ∈ R</p>
<p>(2, 2) ∈ R</p>
<p>(3, 3) ∈ R</p>
<p>(4, 4) ∈ R</p>
<p>(1, 3) ∈ R then (3, 1) ∈ R</p>
<p>(2, 4) ∈ R then (4, 2) ∈ R</p>
<p>The relation is symmetric</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>For Transitive:</strong></span></p>
<p>If (a, b) ∈ R, (b, c) ∈ R then (a, c) ∈ R</p>
<p>(1, 1) ∈ R</p>
<p>(2, 2) ∈ R</p>
<p>(3, 3) ∈ R</p>
<p>(4, 4) ∈ R</p>
<p>(1, 3) ∈ R,  (3, 1) ∈ R then (1, 1) ∈ R</p>
<p>(2, 4) ∈ R,  (4, 2) ∈ R then (2, 2) ∈ R</p>
<p>Hence, the given relation is an equivalence relation.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Problem Part:</strong></span></p>
<p>Given,</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-6461 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/ds-qnbank-2078-sd-ct.jpg?resize=369%2C215&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="369" height="215" srcset="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/ds-qnbank-2078-sd-ct.jpg?w=860&amp;ssl=1 860w, https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/ds-qnbank-2078-sd-ct.jpg?resize=768%2C447&amp;ssl=1 768w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 369px) 100vw, 369px" /></p>
<p>Lets find maximum flow from S to D using S-D cut method:</p>
<div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; height: 240px;">
