<h2>Group B: Attemps any EIGHT questions (8 x 5 = 40)</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>List any one example of tautology. Represent the following sentences into predicate logic.</p>
<ol>
<li>Not all employees are loyal</li>
<li>All students having good attitude are lovable.</li>
</ol</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>One example of a tautology is &#8220;Either it will rain tomorrow, or it will not rain tomorrow.&#8221; This statement is a tautology because it is always true, regardless of whether it actually rains tomorrow or not.</p>
<p>To represent the given sentences in predicate logic:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>Not all employees are loyal</li>
</ol>
<p>Let E(x) represent &#8220;x is an employee&#8221; and L(x) represent &#8220;x is loyal&#8221;. Then the given sentence can be represented in predicate logic as:</p>
<p>¬(∀x E(x) → L(x))</p>
<p>This can be read as &#8220;It is not true that for all x, if x is an employee, then x is loyal.&#8221;</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>All students having good attitude are lovable</li>
</ol>
<p>Let S(x) represent &#8220;x is a student&#8221;, G(x) represent &#8220;x has a good attitude&#8221;, and L(x) represent &#8220;x is lovable&#8221;. Then the given sentence can be represented in predicate logic as:</p>
<p>∀x (S(x) ∧ G(x)) → L(x)</p>
<p>This can be read as &#8220;For all x, if x is a student and x has a good attitude, then x is lovable.&#8221;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>Prove that “If the product of two integers a and b are even then either a is even or b is even”, using the contradiction method.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>We will prove the statement by contradiction.</p>
<p>Suppose that the product of two integers a and b is even, but neither a nor b is even. This means that both a and b are odd.</p>
<p>Let a = 2k + 1 and b = 2m + 1, where k and m are integers. Then, their product is:</p>
<p>ab = (2k + 1)(2m + 1) = 4km + 2k + 2m + 1 = 2(2km + k + m) + 1</p>
<p>Since 2km + k + m is an integer, ab is odd, which contradicts the assumption that ab is even.</p>
<p>Therefore, we can conclude that if the product of two integers a and b is even, then either a is even or b is even.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>Use Chinese Remainder Theorem to find the value of x such that x = 0 ( MOD 2) , x = 2 (MOD 3) and x = 3 (MOD 5).</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Given :</p>
<p><strong>a</strong><sub><strong>1</strong> </sub>= 0 <strong>m</strong><sub><strong>1</strong></sub> = 2</p>
<p><strong>a</strong><sub><strong>2</strong></sub> = 2 <strong>m</strong><sub><strong>2</strong></sub> = 3</p>
<p><strong>a</strong><sub><strong>3</strong></sub> = 3 <strong>m</strong><sub><strong>3</strong></sub> = 5</p>
<p>To find the value of x : we will use the solution,</p>
<p><strong>x = a</strong><sub><strong>1</strong></sub><strong> M</strong><sub><strong>1</strong></sub><strong> Y</strong><sub><strong>1</strong></sub><strong> + a</strong><sub><strong>2</strong></sub><strong> M</strong><sub><strong>2</strong></sub><strong> Y</strong><sub><strong>2</strong></sub><strong> + a</strong><sub><strong>3</strong></sub><strong> M</strong><sub><strong>3</strong></sub><strong> Y</strong><sub><strong>3</strong></sub><strong> _ _ _ _ _ a</strong><sub><strong>k</strong></sub><strong> M</strong><sub><strong>k</strong></sub><strong> Y</strong><sub><strong>k</strong></sub><strong> ( MOD M)</strong></p>
<p><strong>M = m</strong><sub><strong>1</strong></sub><strong> x m</strong><sub><strong>2 </strong></sub><strong>x m</strong><sub><strong>3</strong></sub></p>
<p>= 2 x 3 x 5</p>
<p>= 30</p>
<p><strong>M</strong><sub><strong>1 </strong></sub><strong>= M / m</strong><sub><strong>1</strong></sub><strong> M</strong><sub><strong>2 </strong></sub><strong>= M / m</strong><sub><strong>2</strong></sub><strong> M</strong><sub><strong>3 </strong></sub><strong>= M / m</strong><sub><strong>3</strong></sub></p>
<p>= 30 / 2 = 30 / 3 = 30 / 5</p>
<p>= 15 = 10 = 6</p>
<p>now, finding the value of Y<sub>1</sub> , Y<sub>2</sub> and Y<sub>3</sub></p>
<p><strong>M</strong><sub><strong>1</strong></sub><strong> Y</strong><sub><strong>1</strong></sub><strong> = 1 MOD m</strong><sub><strong>1</strong></sub><strong> M</strong><sub><strong>2</strong></sub><strong> Y</strong><sub><strong>2</strong></sub><strong> = 1 MOD m</strong><sub><strong>2</strong></sub><strong> M</strong><sub><strong>3</strong></sub><strong> Y</strong><sub><strong>3</strong></sub><strong> = 1 MOD m</strong><sub><strong>3</strong></sub></p>
<p>15 Y<sub>1 </sub>= 1 MOD 2 10 Y<sub>2</sub> = 1 MOD 3 6 Y<sub>3 </sub> = 1 MOD 5</p>
<p><strong>Y</strong><sub><strong>1</strong></sub> = 1 <strong>Y</strong><sub><strong>2</strong> </sub> = 1 <strong>Y</strong><sub><strong>3</strong> </sub>= 1</p>
<p>now , putting the values</p>
<p>we get</p>
<p><strong>x = a</strong><sub><strong>1</strong></sub><strong> M</strong><sub><strong>1</strong></sub><strong> Y</strong><sub><strong>1</strong></sub><strong> + a</strong><sub><strong>2</strong></sub><strong> M</strong><sub><strong>2 </strong></sub><strong>Y</strong><sub><strong>2</strong></sub><strong> + a</strong><sub><strong>3</strong></sub><strong> M</strong><sub><strong>3</strong></sub><strong> Y</strong><sub><strong>3 </strong></sub><strong> ( MOD M )</strong></p>
<p>= 0 x 15 x 1 + 2 x 10 x 1 + 3 x 6 x 1 ( MOD 30 )</p>
<p>= 0 + 20 + 18 ( Mod 30 )</p>
<p>= 38 ( Mod 30 )</p>
<p>now putting the value of x ,</p>
<p>To verify:</p>
<p><strong>i) x = 0 ( MOD 2 )</strong> <strong> ii) x = 2 ( MOD 3 ) ii) x = 3 ( MOD 5 )</strong></p>
<p>2 | 38 | 19 3 | 38 | 12 5 | 38 | 7</p>
<p>&#8211; 38 &#8211; 36 &#8211; 35</p>
<p><sub>&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;- &#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212; </sub> &#8212;&#8212;&#8212;-</p>
<p><strong> 0 ( True ) 2 ( True ) 3 ( True )</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
