<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>Given the premises “If it rains or strike holds then the exam will be cancelled. If the doesn’t rain then it will be sunny day. The exam was not cancelled. show that it is sunny day”.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Let p be the proposition &#8220;it rains&#8221; Let q be the proposition &#8220;strike holds&#8221; Let r be the proposition &#8220;the exam is cancelled&#8221; Let s be the proposition &#8220;it is a sunny day&#8221;</p>
<p>The premises can then be rewritten as:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>p ∨ q → r</li>
<li>¬p → s</li>
<li>¬r</li>
</ol>
<p>To show that it is a sunny day, we need to prove that s is true. We can do this by using premises 1 and 3 to show that it is not the case that ¬s is true, i.e. that ¬s is false, which means that s is true.</p>
<p>We can use a proof by contradiction to show that ¬s is false. Assume ¬s is true, i.e. it is not a sunny day. Then, by premise 2, it must have rained. So, we have ¬p → s and p → r, which means that p → (¬s ∧ r) by contraposition.</p>
<p>Since it rained, we have p, so we can conclude that ¬s ∧ r is true. But this contradicts premise 3, which says that r is false (i.e. the exam was not cancelled). Therefore, ¬s must be false, which means that s is true. Hence, it is a sunny day.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>Find the value of -2 MOD 3 and 3<sup>1</sup><sup>5</sup> MOD 5. Illustrate an example to show the join operation between any two boolean matrixes.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The value of</p>
<p><strong>a) -2 MOD 3 =  1</strong></p>
<p>To calculate this, you can follow these steps:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Divide -2 by 3, which gives you -0.6666&#8230;</li>
<li>Round towards zero to get the quotient, which is -0.</li>
<li>Calculate the remainder using the formula: remainder = dividend &#8211; (divisor * quotient). In this case, the remainder is -2 &#8211; (3 * 0) = -2.</li>
<li>Add the divisor (3) to the remainder (-2) to get the final result, which is 1.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>b) 3^15 MOD 5 = 2</strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>Starting with the base (3), repeatedly square and reduce modulo 5 for each bit.
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>3^1 MOD 5 = 3</li>
<li>3^2 MOD 5 = 4</li>
<li>3^4 MOD 5 = (3^2 MOD 5)^2 MOD 5 = 4^2 MOD 5 = 1</li>
<li>3^8 MOD 5 = (3^4 MOD 5)^2 MOD 5 = 1^2 MOD 5 = 1</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Multiply together the values that correspond to a 1 bit in the binary form:
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>3^15 MOD 5 = 3 * 4 * 1 * 1 MOD 5 = 12 MOD 5 = 2</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The given two Boolean matrices is</p>
<p>A = <span id="MathJax-Span-157" class="mrow"><span id="MathJax-Span-158" class="mrow"><span id="MathJax-Span-159" class="mo">[100], B=[101]</span></span></span></p>
<p>join two matrices AvB</p>
<p>AvB=[101]</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>Given an example of fallacy. State the necessary and sufficient conditions for a graph to have Euler path and Euler circuit.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><header>
<h1><span style="font-size: 16px;">Definition of Fallacy</span></h1>
</header>
<div class="post-single-content box mark-links entry-content">
<div class="thecontent clearfix">
<p>an idea or belief that is false but many people think is true</p>
<p><strong>Examples of Fallacy in a sentence</strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
<li>Having money makes you happy is a fallacy because happiness has nothing to do with wealth.</li>
<li>While the business plan sounds good on paper, it is built on the fallacy that people will pay thirty dollars to see a movie.</li>
</ol>
<p><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eulerian_path" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow">Eulerian Path </a>is a path in graph that visits every edge exactly once. Eulerian Circuit is an Eulerian Path which starts and ends on the same vertex.</p>
<h1>Necessary and sufficient conditions for Euler paths</h1>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">Euler circuit if and only if it has exactly two vertices of odd degree.</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">Proof:</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">(ONLY IF) Assume the graph has an Euler path but not a circuit.</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">Notice that every time the path passes through a vertex, it contributes</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">2 to the degree of the vertex (1 when it enters, 1 when it leaves).</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">Obviously the first and the last vertices will have odd degree and all</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">the other vertices &#8211; even degree.</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">(IF) Assume exactly two vertices, u and v, have odd degree.</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">If we connect these two vertices, then every vertex will have even degree.</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">By Theorem 1, there is an Euler circuit in such a graph.</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">If we remove the added edge {u,v} from this circuit, we will get an</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">Euler path for the original graph.</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">End of proof</ul>
<h1>Necessary and sufficient conditions for Euler circuits</h1>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li style="list-style-type: none;">
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">Obviously a non-connected graph cannot have an Euler path unless it has isolated vertices.</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">Theorem 1. A connected multigraph has an Euler circuit if and only if each of its vertices has even degree.</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div class="post-single-content box mark-links entry-content">
<div class="thecontent clearfix">
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li style="list-style-type: none;">
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">Why “only if”:</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">Assume the graph has an Euler circuit.</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">Observe that every time the circuit passes through a vertex, it</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">contributes 2 to the vertex’s degree, since the circuit enters via an edge</ul>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">incident with this vertex and leaves via another such edge.</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Find the GCD of 24 and 32 using Extended Euclidean algorithm.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><h3>GCD of 24 and 32 by Euclidean Algorithm</h3>
<p>As per the Euclidean Algorithm, GCF(X, Y) = GCF(Y, X mod Y)<br />
where X &gt; Y and mod is the modulo operator.</p>
<p>Here X = 32 and Y = 24</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>EUCLID(32, 24) = EUCLID(24, 32 mod 24) = EUCLID(24, 8)</li>
<li>EUCLID(24, 8) = EUCLID(8, 24 mod 8) = EUCLID(8, 0)</li>
<li>EUCLID(8, 0) = 8 (∵ EUCLID(X, 0) = |X|, where X ≠ 0)</li>
</ul>
<div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">R1</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">R2</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">R</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">Q</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">32</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">24</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">8</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">24</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">8</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">0</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">4</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">8</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">0</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">&#8211;</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">&#8211;</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>Therefore, the value of GCF of 24 and 32 is 8.</p>
</div>
